34. Find First and Last Position of Element in Sorted Array
Problem

Given a sorted array nums (non-decreasing order) and a target value:

Return the first occurrence index of the target.
Return the last occurrence index of the target.
If the target does not exist, return [-1, -1].
Example
nums = [5,7,7,8,8,10]
target = 8

Output = [3,4]
Key Observation

The array is sorted, so Binary Search can be used.

A normal Binary Search stops as soon as it finds the target.

However, in this problem we need:

First occurrence
Last occurrence

Therefore, we perform Binary Search twice:

Find First Occurrence
Find Last Occurrence
Why Two Binary Searches?

Consider:

Index: 0 1 2 3 4 5
Value: 5 7 7 8 8 10

Normal Binary Search may find:

index = 4

But we still don't know:

Is 4 the first occurrence?
Is 4 the last occurrence?

So we continue searching even after finding the target.

Approach 1: Find First Occurrence

When target is found:

ans = mid;
high = mid - 1;
Why move left?

Because there may be another occurrence of the target before mid.

Example:

5 7 7 8 8 10
      ↑
   another 8 may exist

We store the current answer and continue searching left.

First Occurrence Code
public int findFirst(int[] nums, int target) {

    int low = 0;
    int high = nums.length - 1;
    int ans = -1;

    while(low <= high) {

        int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

        if(nums[mid] == target) {
            ans = mid;
            high = mid - 1;
        }

        else if(nums[mid] < target) {
            low = mid + 1;
        }

        else {
            high = mid - 1;
        }
    }

    return ans;
}
Approach 2: Find Last Occurrence

When target is found:

ans = mid;
low = mid + 1;
Why move right?

Because there may be another occurrence of the target after mid.

Example:

5 7 7 8 8 10
        ↑
    another 8 may exist

We store the current answer and continue searching right.

Last Occurrence Code
public int findLast(int[] nums, int target) {

    int low = 0;
    int high = nums.length - 1;
    int ans = -1;

    while(low <= high) {

        int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

        if(nums[mid] == target) {
            ans = mid;
            low = mid + 1;
        }

        else if(nums[mid] < target) {
            low = mid + 1;
        }

        else {
            high = mid - 1;
        }
    }

    return ans;
}
Complete Solution
class Solution {

    public int[] searchRange(int[] nums, int target) {

        int first = findFirst(nums, target);
        int last = findLast(nums, target);

        return new int[]{first, last};
    }

    public int findFirst(int[] nums, int target) {

        int low = 0;
        int high = nums.length - 1;
        int ans = -1;

        while(low <= high) {

            int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

            if(nums[mid] == target) {
                ans = mid;
                high = mid - 1;
            }
            else if(nums[mid] < target) {
                low = mid + 1;
            }
            else {
                high = mid - 1;
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }

    public int findLast(int[] nums, int target) {

        int low = 0;
        int high = nums.length - 1;
        int ans = -1;

        while(low <= high) {

            int mid = low + (high - low) / 2;

            if(nums[mid] == target) {
                ans = mid;
                low = mid + 1;
            }
            else if(nums[mid] < target) {
                low = mid + 1;
            }
            else {
                high = mid - 1;
            }
        }

        return ans;
    }
}
Dry Run
Input
nums = [5,7,7,8,8,10]
target = 8
Finding First Occurrence
mid = 2 → 7
low = 3

mid = 4 → 8
ans = 4
high = 3

mid = 3 → 8
ans = 3
high = 2

stop

Result:

first = 3
Finding Last Occurrence
mid = 2 → 7
low = 3

mid = 4 → 8
ans = 4
low = 5

mid = 5 → 10
high = 4

stop

Result:

last = 4
Final Answer
[3,4]
Why Do We Need ans?

Suppose:

nums = [8,8,8,8]

When we find a target:

ans = mid;

We save the valid index.

Then we continue searching left or right.

Without ans, we would lose the correct position while continuing the search.

Edge Cases
Target Not Present
nums = [5,7,7,8,8,10]
target = 6

Output:

[-1,-1]
Empty Array
nums = []
target = 0

Output:

[-1,-1]
Complexity Analysis
Time Complexity

Two Binary Searches:

O(log n) + O(log n)

Overall:

O(log n)
Space Complexity
O(1)
Important Pattern
First Occurrence
if(nums[mid] == target) {
    ans = mid;
    high = mid - 1;
}

👉 Save answer and move LEFT.

Last Occurrence
if(nums[mid] == target) {
    ans = mid;
    low = mid + 1;
}

👉 Save answer and move RIGHT.

Key Takeaway

This problem introduces a common Binary Search pattern:

Instead of stopping when the target is found, store the answer and continue searching in the required direction.

Move Left → First Occurrence
Move Right → Last Occurrence

